---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { href } from '../utils';

// Update this date whenever the policy facts on this page are re-verified
// (the weekly policy-watch workflow opens a PR when source pages change).
const lastVerified = 'June 2026';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Current Policy"
  description="What Saint Paul Public Schools' technology and device policy actually says, how Minnesota state law shapes it, and where the gaps are."
>
  <h1>Current Policy</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    What the rules actually say — at the State Capitol, at 360 Colborne, and in
    your student's school building.
  </p>
  <p class="updated">Last verified: {lastVerified}. This site's automated monitor checks the source pages weekly and flags changes.</p>

  <h2>How the layers fit together</h2>
  <p>
    School technology rules in Minnesota are set at three levels, and knowing
    which level controls what is the key to changing any of it:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Level</th><th>Who decides</th><th>What it controls today</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>State law</strong></td>
        <td>Minnesota Legislature</td>
        <td>
          Sets the floor. Minn. Stat. § 121A.73 required every district to adopt
          a cell phone policy by March 15, 2025 — but (so far) lets each district
          decide what the policy says.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>District policy</strong></td>
        <td>SPPS Board of Education</td>
        <td>
          The "Students and Personal Electronic Devices" policy (adopted February
          2025): phones off and out of sight during the school day, districtwide.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>School procedures</strong></td>
        <td>Each principal &amp; site council</td>
        <td>
          Implementation details — lunch and passing time, storage, enforcement,
          and any high-school exceptions. This is why rules differ between
          buildings.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The practical takeaway: if you want stronger rules at your child's school,
    the principal and site council can act tomorrow. If you want consistency
    across Saint Paul, that's the school board. If you want consistency across
    Minnesota, that's the Legislature.
  </p>

  <h2>What Minnesota law requires</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/121A.73">Minn. Stat. § 121A.73</a>
    made Minnesota one of the states that mandates a local policy without
    dictating its content. That may be about to change: <strong>SF 508 / HF 2516</strong>,
    pending in the 2026 session, would ban phones and smartwatches entirely for
    grades K–8 and in classrooms for grades 9–12, statewide, starting in 2026–27.
    Twenty-six states already require districts to ban or limit phones — 22 of
    those laws passed in 2025 alone. Minnesota currently mandates less than most
    of its neighbors.
  </p>

  <h2>What SPPS policy says</h2>
  <p>
    The board-approved policy, in effect since fall 2025, requires personal
    electronic devices to be <strong>turned off and out of sight</strong> during
    the school day — left at home, in a locker, or off in a backpack — with
    exceptions for documented medical monitoring and emergencies. Each school
    publishes its own implementation procedures. The board's stated rationale
    when it passed the policy: academic performance and student mental health.
  </p>
  <div class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>What the policy doesn't cover.</strong> The 2025 policy governs
      students' <em>personal</em> devices. It says nothing about the
      district-issued iPad on every desk: which apps are on it, how much of the
      school day is spent on it, what data it collects, or whether its use is
      evaluated against learning outcomes. A decade after the 1:1 rollout, there
      is no public, recurring review of whether the program helps children learn.
      That gap — not the phone policy — is where SPPS most lags the districts on
      our <a href={href('/compare/')}>comparison page</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Primary sources</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="https://www.spps.org/about/board-of-education/board-policies-procedures">SPPS Board Policies &amp; Procedures</a> — the district's official policy library
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://www.spps.org/families/students-rights-responsibilities">SPPS Rights &amp; Responsibilities handbook</a> — how the rules are communicated to families
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/121A.73">Minn. Stat. § 121A.73</a> — the state cell phone policy mandate
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How this page stays current</h2>
  <p>
    A weekly automated job fetches the SPPS policy pages and the Minnesota
    statute above, compares them to stored snapshots, and opens an alert when
    anything changes — so updates here follow district and state changes within
    days, not years. The monitoring code is
    <a href="https://github.com/kgerbner/SPPSEdTech">public</a>.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
